WEBVTT

00:02.593 --> 00:04.808
<i>- We decided to move on.</i>
- Are you doing OK?

00:04.833 --> 00:07.167
- Not yet.
- Just because it didn't happen

00:07.202 --> 00:09.702
with him doesn't mean it
won't happen with somebody else.

00:09.730 --> 00:11.529
- Martha's right.
- Maybe.

00:11.565 --> 00:13.365
How long do you think our kids
can go without getting along?

00:13.400 --> 00:15.500
I don't know. Which one
of them is more stubborn?

00:15.535 --> 00:18.620
If we fake a truce while we're
with our parents, then they can

00:18.645 --> 00:21.247
- at least get on with getting married.
- <i>What kind of ring do you want?</i>

00:21.248 --> 00:23.452
<i>There is a certain ring
that I've always wanted.</i>

00:23.487 --> 00:25.227
- A Merriwick ring?
- <i>It's supposed to bring</i>

00:25.263 --> 00:27.390
<i>a lasting marriage full of happiness</i>

00:27.404 --> 00:29.091
<i>to any bride who wears it.</i>

00:30.207 --> 00:33.141
(SOFT MUSIC)

00:33.176 --> 00:35.844
♪♪♪

00:38.882 --> 00:41.182
- When did he ask you?!
- The night

00:41.218 --> 00:43.485
- of your son's wedding.
- Oh!

00:43.520 --> 00:45.487
And just yesterday, he gave me this ring.

00:45.522 --> 00:46.963
- Oh!
- It really does

00:46.998 --> 00:49.357
- look beautiful on you.
- Where on earth did Sam

00:49.393 --> 00:51.660
- find such a thing?
- Oh...

00:51.695 --> 00:54.362
He wouldn't tell me exactly, but somehow

00:54.398 --> 00:56.831
he knew it was the perfect ring for me.

00:56.867 --> 01:00.235
Well, I'm happy for you. You
and Sam deserve the very best.

01:00.270 --> 01:02.537
Will you be making a formal announcement?

01:02.572 --> 01:04.706
I don't think so.
Sam's not really into making

01:04.741 --> 01:07.208
a big show of things.
We have told our kids, though.

01:07.244 --> 01:10.612
Oh! Nick and Grace are gonna
be brother and sister!

01:10.647 --> 01:12.614
Yeah. They've been friends
long enough that we hope it'll

01:12.649 --> 01:16.017
- be a pretty easy transition.
- They get along well.

01:16.053 --> 01:18.887
Yeah, most of the time. We'll
see if they can keep that up.

01:20.624 --> 01:23.191
So, I understand
congratulations are in order!

01:23.226 --> 01:25.126
Oh, no, no, no, no, no! You don't

01:25.162 --> 01:28.630
congratulate the bride-to-be.
You say, "best wishes."

01:28.665 --> 01:30.632
Why can't I say congratulations?

01:30.667 --> 01:32.934
You congratulate the groom on obtaining

01:32.969 --> 01:36.204
- such a spectacular prize.
- So women are prizes now?

01:36.239 --> 01:38.573
I don't make the rules, dear.
I just follow them.

01:39.336 --> 01:40.942
Well, I think Sam

01:40.977 --> 01:44.112
is a pretty great prize too,
so congratulations!

01:44.147 --> 01:47.248
- Thank you! And I agree.
- Can I see the ring?

01:47.284 --> 01:51.252
- Oh, of course!
- (GASPING)

01:51.288 --> 01:52.855
Oh, wow!

01:52.891 --> 01:55.123
I am trying not to be jealous right now,

01:55.158 --> 01:58.093
and not just because I thought
I would get one of these

01:58.128 --> 02:00.895
from Ben, but because it's so gorgeous!

02:00.931 --> 02:02.764
How are you doing, not being together?

02:02.799 --> 02:06.267
I'm OK. It was time to move on
for both of us.

02:06.303 --> 02:08.269
It's just so weird.

02:08.305 --> 02:10.604
You know, I've been out
of the dating game for so long,

02:10.639 --> 02:12.607
I don't know how to get back in it.

02:12.642 --> 02:15.276
I'm sure you'll find yourself
with plenty of options.

02:15.312 --> 02:17.946
Well, I'll believe it when I see it.

02:18.949 --> 02:21.449
Anyway, enough "boo-hoo me" talk.

02:21.485 --> 02:23.265
What can I get for you?

02:23.301 --> 02:25.286
Are you still serving
that artichoke omelette?

02:25.322 --> 02:27.288
No. It was a special yesterday,

02:27.324 --> 02:30.425
but I can make one for you if you'd like.

02:30.460 --> 02:32.160
Thanks.

02:32.195 --> 02:34.295
Ooh! Could you make me one
also? It sounds delicious.

02:34.331 --> 02:37.132
- Yeah, me too.
- Look at that!

02:37.167 --> 02:38.766
You just sold three.

02:38.801 --> 02:41.469
Maybe you should make it
today's special too and...

02:41.505 --> 02:43.638
see if it brings in more people
who wanna try it.

02:43.673 --> 02:46.641
Yeah. I'll go put it
on the board out front.

02:46.676 --> 02:48.810
I wish that I could come up

02:48.845 --> 02:50.779
with ideas as easily as you two do.

02:50.814 --> 02:53.314
I'm supposed to speak at the rededication

02:53.350 --> 02:56.651
of the Salt Creek Bridge, and I
have no idea what I'm gonna say.

02:56.686 --> 02:58.731
I remember when that was first dedicated.

02:58.767 --> 03:01.489
Everybody does! That's because
the mayor at the time

03:01.525 --> 03:03.491
delivered a speech,
which many consider to be

03:03.527 --> 03:05.994
- one of his very best.
- Who was the mayor?

03:06.029 --> 03:07.896
Martha's husband. (INAUDIBLE SPEAKING)

03:07.931 --> 03:11.332
I don't know where he found
his inspiration, but his words

03:11.368 --> 03:13.334
left such a lasting impression

03:13.370 --> 03:15.470
that people are still
quoting them to this day.

03:15.505 --> 03:17.839
So, you have a lot to live up to.

03:17.874 --> 03:20.341
Yes. Well, thank you for reminding me.

03:20.377 --> 03:24.312
- Oops. Sorry.
- Hmm!

03:24.347 --> 03:27.215
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

03:27.250 --> 03:29.184
Here. Lift your side higher.

03:29.219 --> 03:31.186
I'm trying! You need to lower yours.

03:31.221 --> 03:34.022
- I'm trying! It's heavy.
- I don't know

03:34.057 --> 03:37.192
- why we had to do this.
- Because my mom asked us to.

03:37.227 --> 03:39.360
And when we take it in there
right now, we are going

03:39.396 --> 03:41.196
to pretend like everything is fine.

03:41.231 --> 03:44.332
- I know the rules, Grace.
- Then let's go.

03:45.042 --> 03:47.702
- Here we go!
- Oh, great! You can put it right there.

03:47.737 --> 03:49.704
- OK.
- Yeah.

03:49.739 --> 03:52.740
- You still got a hold?
- Yeah. Thank you.

03:52.776 --> 03:55.376
That looks really nice.

03:55.412 --> 03:57.378
- Yeah.
- Good, 'cause my best

03:57.414 --> 04:00.048
piano-moving days are behind me.

04:00.083 --> 04:03.351
Thanks. You know, it was just
gathering dust in a back room,

04:03.386 --> 04:06.020
and I thought it'd be nice to
have music in here for a change.

04:06.056 --> 04:08.089
Well, let's see how it sounds.

04:08.124 --> 04:10.058
♪♪♪

04:11.595 --> 04:13.962
Sam, I didn't know you played piano!

04:13.997 --> 04:17.398
Ah, just enough so people think I'm good.

04:17.434 --> 04:19.399
I've gotta go study for my German test,

04:19.435 --> 04:21.935
- so I'll see you later.
- Bye.

04:21.971 --> 04:23.455
Thank you.

04:24.774 --> 04:27.408
- Did I hear music in here?
- You did!

04:27.444 --> 04:30.078
- Sam's pretty good, huh?
- Well, why don't you sit down

04:30.113 --> 04:33.047
and play some more? I bet Cassie
especially would love that.

04:33.083 --> 04:35.149
(CHUCKLING) Oh, happy to.

04:35.185 --> 04:38.419
Oh! What's in there?

04:38.455 --> 04:40.255
Oh, wow.

04:40.290 --> 04:44.592
- Look at all that.
- These are songs from my day.

04:44.628 --> 04:46.661
"Words and Music by Jacob Hayward."

04:46.696 --> 04:49.797
- Wait. Who's Jacob Hayward?
- He was a songwriter

04:49.833 --> 04:52.333
in the 1930s.
He actually lived in Middleton

04:52.369 --> 04:54.435
- near the end of his life.
- Just as popular

04:54.471 --> 04:56.471
as Cole Porter, the Gershwins,

04:56.506 --> 04:58.907
- or Irving Berlin.
- Yeah. Hayward's songs

04:58.942 --> 05:02.443
really affected people
in personal and unique ways.

05:04.621 --> 05:06.447
Wait. This one's hand-written.

05:06.483 --> 05:08.449
Oh. That looks like an original piece...

05:08.485 --> 05:10.351
- Hmm.
- By Jacob Hayward.

05:10.387 --> 05:13.454
Wow. Look, it's got his initials here.

05:13.490 --> 05:16.624
Wait. Do you think that he
might've stayed at Grey House?

05:16.660 --> 05:19.460
Maybe he even wrote that song right here.

05:19.496 --> 05:22.797
It doesn't have any lyrics
to the tune. No title.

05:22.832 --> 05:25.500
I know. Let's just see
how it goes in the key of F.

05:25.535 --> 05:28.136
♪♪♪

05:33.376 --> 05:35.143
That's nice.

05:35.178 --> 05:38.479
- Yeah.
- You know, I'm pretty sure

05:38.515 --> 05:39.760
I know all of Haywood's songs,

05:39.796 --> 05:41.397
but I've never heard that one before.

05:41.433 --> 05:44.319
Yeah, me neither. Hmm.
Maybe it never got recorded.

05:44.354 --> 05:47.989
It'd be a shame.
It'd make a nice love song.

05:48.024 --> 05:51.326
I don't know if I
hear a love song, exactly.

05:51.361 --> 05:53.328
I guess different people
can hear the same song

05:53.363 --> 05:57.165
- in different ways.
- Music is mysterious that way.

05:57.200 --> 05:59.367
It really is.

05:59.402 --> 06:01.669
"Play it again, Sam."

06:01.705 --> 06:03.338
(CHUCKLING)

06:03.373 --> 06:06.474
♪♪♪

